Want the lowdown on European markets? In your inbox before the open, every day. Sign up here. European stocks climbed with U.S. futures despite a downbeat session in Asia as investors shrugged off lingering doubts about global growth and the outlook for trade to end the week on a positive note. Treasuries held steady and the dollar advanced. Banks and media shares helped drive gains in the Stoxx Europe 600 Index after a lackluster start, while contracts on the S&P 500 erased an earlier loss to turn higher as the latest round of U.S.-China trade negotiations broke off with a promise to continue talks next week. Asian shares retreated, with Chinese stocks falling as weak factory prices highlighted the tough environment for industrial profitability, adding to other disappointing economic data. In the U.K., the pound saw choppy trading after Parliament refused to endorse Prime Minister Theresa May’s approach to resolving the Brexit deadlock. Trade tensions between the U.S. and Beijing continue to dictate sentiment as the two sides race to reach a deal that would avert a tariff increase on Chinese goods by March 1. Growth concerns have also plagued investors after China’s factory inflation decelerated on softening demand. In Washington, Congress sent President Donald Trump legislation he said he’ll sign to avoid another government shutdown as a new dispute looms over his decision to declare a national emergency to get more federal money for a border wall. Elsewhere, oil climbed on supply cuts and reduced output, while emerging market shares fell. These are the main moves in markets: — With assistance by Reade Pickert, Garfield Clinton Reynolds, Cormac Mullen, and Adam Haigh